title: Notes from a FIlm Festival
contentMarkdown:
All film festivals are equal, but some festivals are more equal than others. The Kolkata International Film Festival, otherwise known as KIFF, is one such festival.

This past week, the city hosted the 31st edition of KIFF. The state government went all out with promotions, with banners and hoardings everywhere, and though there are no official numbers, I am sure this year saw a record turnout. Being from Kolkata, KIFF is the only film festival I have ever attended in earnest, starting in 2018 and continuing until 2021, which was when I lost my delegate card. The application process for a new delegate card is notoriously difficult, and my applications were not even processed until this year, when I had the honour of having a film in official selection. My film Acts of Kindness was part of the National Competition for Short Films. To say it was a dream come true would be an understatement.

Being a director at a film festival has its perks. People react positively to your director card, all areas of the festival suddenly become accessible, and your opinions seem to carry more weight in post screening discussions. Perhaps the biggest perk is that you can walk up to any big filmmaker and talk to them as an equal, not just as an admirer, but as a colleague. But it does involve a lot of running around: scrambling for passes for family, friends, and crew, chasing after press coverage, and trying to navigate the festival’s difficult management. For the first screening, I was just a mass of nerves. No screening ever goes without a hitch, and this was no exception. The sound was horrible, and I don’t know how much the audience was able to understand. The second screening was smaller but went far more smoothly. This being KIFF, both screenings were packed to the brim, making them the largest audiences I have ever had. That was nice.

I have been part of film festivals before, but never like this. I was genuinely overwhelmed by the support and love that poured in from all sides, all the more so because KIFF is the main cinema event in our part of the world. To be honest, the attention made me a bit uncomfortable. I am far more used to being hunched over a laptop in my bedroom, spending months poring over a tiny viewport, making small tweaks to a film I am sure no one will ever see. I spend countless days writing and revising a script, making it more personal with every draft, because I have the freedom of being unknown. Seeing the same film projected on a giant screen feels a bit surreal, as does the personal becoming public. But at the end of the day, this is why I started making films, isn’t it? What is the point of art if it is not shared? I would not miss it for the world.

Amidst the chaos, I still managed to watch a fair number of films, making full use of my hard won delegate card. From Ghatak to Peckinpah to Radu Jude, my viewings  were eclectic, to say the least. Now that the festival is over, life feels a tiny bit emptier. I am beginning to miss that feeling that once made me uncomfortable. Then again, I am sure I will have reason to feel it again someday.
